      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Mideast Violence Strikes a Raw Nerve</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jameel Jaffer letter, replying to Lawrence S Eagleburger's Oct 11 Op-Ed article, says a large part of Palestinian outrage was born not from Ariel Sharon's visit to Temple Mount, but from Israel's disproportionately severe conduct since then</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Failure With Many Fathers,'' by Lawrence S. Eagleburger (Op-Ed, Oct. 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Failure With Many Fathers,'' by Lawrence S. Eagleburger (Op-Ed, Oct. 11):</p>
        <p>Mr. Eagleburger says that Palestinian outrage at Ariel Sharon's visit to the compound that is known by Muslims as the Noble Sanctuary and by Jews as the Temple Mount was out of proportion to the crime. To be fair, a similar criticism might also be applied to Israel.</p>
        <p>Israel's soldiers have killed scores of Arab civilians, most for throwing stones, and some for merely being in the wrong place at the wrong time.</p>
        <p>A large part of Palestinian outrage was born not from Mr. Sharon's unfortunate visit, but from Israel's disproportionately severe conduct since then.</p>
        <p>JAMEEL JAFFER  Ottawa, Oct. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
